content: we will now begin our lesson.
As you know, the following 2 weeks will be very decisive for the future of renju.
In December 31, the list of all opening rules proposals will be locked.
And the best choice will be found from the list by May 2006.
We have exactly 2 weeks, to make proposals for new rules.
Did you all think about any ideas? If you have an idea, you can introduce it here.
course not,, december 31 is far away :p
How many of you have checked the Forum in renjuclass that discusses the opening rules?
In my oppinion 1st  have to put one of 26 openings
I just read the rule of 7 or 8 proposals.
If you care about the future of renju, then you can read about these.
because the chosen new rule may last next 30 years at least.
so it really is an important moment.
Today, I would like to analyse another version of opening rule.
some of them seems too complicated
2 weeks ago we learned about Jonsson's rule, with 1-3 fifth moves.
there are alot of variation of "jonsson rule" seems many like the idea of it....
Shanghai renju club suggests 1-5 fifth moves.
and understand their differences, advantages and disadvantages,
Who can tell me 1 advantage and 1 disadvantage of Shanghai rule, compared to the Jonsson's rule?
Advantage Shangai: more variation, Advantage of Jonsson: less stupid positions
hmmm.. what you said is actually true.
thats the only advantage and only disadvantage.
But right now, both advantage and disadvantage is our guess only,
we have not really tested it.
we just made logical assumption that if white player suggests 5 fifth moves, then the 4th move can be very far.
and its almost impossible for the opponent to make the right choice
and he will lose without fight
to see if its really a problem or not.
would you choose black or white?
in fact.. if this happens in real game, and someone says, 5 fifth,
then i really have no idea!
perhaps, in sharp opening, 5 5th is too many ?
we can use our "feeling" to decide
if here, i say 4 fifth moves
as you know, in such sharp opening, there basically cannot be any draw
so what you decide now, its either your win or loss
how about others? black or white?
which one do you pick, if you are white?
i think, the traditional 4th moves are maybe not very confusing
but now lets look at some "crazy" 4th moves
this is sure win for black
this is sure win for any 6
good job both of you! thank you!
I am white, I say: 5 fifth moves. do you choose black or white?
